{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Rsj1pkNpZEEJ25n9iN64ZV","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect. I've read the entire db.ts file. Here's the comprehensive summary you need:\n\n## Referral-Related Types (Lines 127–166)\n\n```typescript\nexport interface ReferralCode {\n  id: number;\n  wallet: string;\n  code: string;\n  created_at: Date;\n  updated_at: Date;\n}\n\nexport interface ReferralLink {\n  id: number;\n  referrer_wallet: string;\n  referee_wallet: string;\n  created_at: Date;\n}\n\nexport interface ReferralEarning {\n  id: number;\n  referrer_wallet: string;\n  referee_wallet: string;\n  round_id: string;\n  game_type: string;\n  wager_lamports: number;\n  fee_lamports: number;\n  referrer_earned_lamports: number;\n  referrer_rate_bps: number;\n  referee_rebate_lamports: number;\n  referee_rebate_rate_bps: number;\n  created_at: Date;\n}\n\nexport interface ReferralStats {\n  referred_count: number;\n  active_count: number;\n  total_volume_lamports: string;\n  total_earned_lamports: string;\n  pending_lamports: string;\n}\n```\n\n## Db Interface — Referral Method Signatures (Lines 302–365)\n\n### Codes\n```typescript\n/** Insert a new referral code for a wallet. Throws on duplicate wallet or code. */\ninsertReferralCode(wallet: string, code: string): Promise<ReferralCode>;\n\n/** Get a wallet's referral code. Returns `undefined` if none set. */\ngetReferralCodeByWallet(wallet: string): Promise<ReferralCode | undefined>;\n\n/** Look up a referral code record by code string. Returns `undefined` if not found. */\ngetReferralCodeByCode(code: string): Promise<ReferralCode | undefined>;\n\n/** Set or replace a wallet's referral code (INSERT … ON CONFLICT UPDATE). */\nupsertReferralCode(wallet: string, code: string): Promise<ReferralCode>;\n```\n\n### Links\n```typescript\n/** Create a referral link (referrer → referee). Throws on duplicate referee. */\ninsertReferralLink(referrerWallet: string, refereeWallet: string): Promise<ReferralLink>;\n\n/** Get the referral link for a referee wallet. Returns `undefined` if not referred. */\ngetReferralLinkByReferee(refereeWallet: string): Promise<ReferralLink | undefined>;\n\n/** Get all referral links where the given wallet is the referrer. */\ngetReferralLinksByReferrer(referrerWallet: string): Promise<ReferralLink[]>;\n```\n\n### Earnings & Stats\n```typescript\n/** Insert a referral earning row. Throws on duplicate (referee_wallet, round_id). */\ninsertReferralEarning(params: {\n  referrerWallet: string;\n  refereeWallet: string;\n  roundId: string;\n  gameType: string;\n  wagerLamports: number;\n  feeLamports: number;\n  referrerEarnedLamports: number;\n  referrerRateBps: number;\n  refereeRebateLamports: number;\n  refereeRebateRateBps: number;\n}): Promise<ReferralEarning>;\n\n/** Get the pending (unclaimed) balance for a wallet. */\ngetPendingBalance(wallet: string): Promise<string>;\n\n/** Get paginated per-game earnings for a wallet (as referrer). Newest first. */\ngetReferralEarnings(wallet: string, page: number, limit: number): Promise<{ items: ReferralEarning[]; totalPages: number }>;\n\n/** Get referral summary stats for a wallet. */\ngetReferralStats(wallet: string): Promise<ReferralStats>;\n```\n\n## Implementation Patterns\n\n### 1. Database Client Creation (Lines 425–427)\n```typescript\nexport function createDb(databaseUrl: string): Db {\n  const sql = postgres(databaseUrl);\n  return { ... };\n}\n```\nThe postgres client is created once and reused for all queries. All methods use template literals with `sql\\`...\\`` syntax.\n\n### 2. Data Normalization Functions (Lines 389–406)\n```typescript\nfunction normalizeReferralEarning(row: ReferralEarning): ReferralEarning {\n  return {\n    ...row,\n    wager_lamports: Number(row.wager_lamports),\n    fee_lamports: Number(row.fee_lamports),\n    referrer_earned_lamports: Number(row.referrer_earned_lamports),\n    referrer_rate_bps: Number(row.referrer_rate_bps),\n    referee_rebate_lamports: Number(row.referee_rebate_lamports),\n    referee_rebate_rate_bps: Number(row.referee_rebate_rate_bps),\n  };\n}\n```\nAll numeric fields from postgres are coerced to JavaScript `Number` type. This pattern is used for every return value.\n\n### 3. Insert Methods with Conflict Handling (Lines 728–735, 791–807)\n```typescript\nasync insertReferralCode(wallet, code) {\n  const rows = await sql<ReferralCode[]>`\n    INSERT INTO referral_codes (wallet, code)\n    VALUES (${wallet}, ${code})\n    RETURNING *\n  `;\n  return rows[0]!;\n}\n\nasync insertReferralEarning(params) {\n  const rows = await sql<ReferralEarning[]>`\n    INSERT INTO referral_earnings (\n      referrer_wallet, referee_wallet, round_id, game_type,\n      wager_lamports, fee_lamports,\n      referrer_earned_lamports, referrer_rate_bps,\n      referee_rebate_lamports, referee_rebate_rate_bps\n    ) VALUES (\n      ${params.referrerWallet}, ${params.refereeWallet}, ${params.roundId}, ${params.gameType},\n      ${params.wagerLamports}, ${params.feeLamports},\n      ${params.referrerEarnedLamports}, ${params.referrerRateBps},\n      ${params.refereeRebateLamports}, ${params.refereeRebateRateBps}\n    )\n    RETURNING *\n  `;\n  return normalizeReferralEarning(rows[0]!);\n}\n```\n- Always use `RETURNING *` to get back the inserted row\n- Return `rows[0]!` with non-null assertion (postgres.js always returns an array)\n- Apply normalization before returning\n\n### 4. Upsert Pattern (Lines 751–761)\n```typescript\nasync upsertReferralCode(wallet, code) {\n  const rows = await sql<ReferralCode[]>`\n    INSERT INTO referral_codes (wallet, code)\n    VALUES (${wallet}, ${code})\n    ON CONFLICT (wallet) DO UPDATE SET\n      code = ${code},\n      updated_at = now()\n    RETURNING *\n  `;\n  return rows[0]!;\n}\n```\nUses `ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE` to atomically replace existing records.\n\n### 5. Get Methods with Optional Returns (Lines 737–748, 774–779)\n```typescript\nasync getReferralCodeByWallet(wallet) {\n  const rows = await sql<ReferralCode[]>`\n    SELECT * FROM referral_codes WHERE wallet = ${wallet}\n  `;\n  return rows[0];\n}\n\nasync getReferralLinkByReferee(refereeWallet) {\n  const rows = await sql<ReferralLink[]>`\n    SELECT * FROM referral_links WHERE referee_wallet = ${refereeWallet}\n  `;\n  return rows[0];\n}\n```\n- Return `rows[0]` (undefined if empty) for single-row queries\n- No normalization needed (no numeric conversions)\n\n### 6. Complex Query with Aggregation (Lines 850–879)\n```typescript\nasync getReferralStats(wallet) {\n  const rows = await sql<ReferralStats[]>`\n    SELECT\n      (SELECT COUNT(*) FROM referral_links WHERE referrer_wallet = ${wallet})::INT\n        AS referred_count,\n      (\n        SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT re.referee_wallet)\n        FROM referral_earnings re\n        JOIN referral_links rl ON rl.referee_wallet = re.referee_wallet AND rl.referrer_wallet = ${wallet}\n        WHERE re.created_at > now() - INTERVAL '7 days'\n      )::INT AS active_count,\n      COALESCE(...) AS total_volume_lamports,\n      COALESCE(...) AS total_earned_lamports,\n      (...) AS pending_lamports\n  `;\n  return rows[0]!;\n}\n```\nBuilds up multiple aggregations in a single query. Uses subqueries and JOINs. Returns the single result row directly.\n\n### 7. Paginated Query (Lines 831–848)\n```typescript\nasync getReferralEarnings(wallet, page, limit) {\n  const offset = (page - 1) * limit;\n  const [countRows, rows] = await Promise.all([\n    sql<{ count: string }[]>`\n      SELECT COUNT(*)::TEXT AS count FROM referral_earnings\n      WHERE referrer_wallet = ${wallet}\n    `,\n    sql<ReferralEarning[]>`\n      SELECT * FROM referral_earnings\n      WHERE referrer_wallet = ${wallet}\n      ORDER BY created_at DESC\n      LIMIT ${limit} OFFSET ${offset}\n    `,\n  ]);\n  const total = Number(countRows[0]!.count);\n  const totalPages = Math.max(1, Math.ceil(total / limit));\n  return { items: rows.map(normalizeReferralEarning), totalPages };\n}\n```\n- Fetches count and paginated results in parallel with `Promise.all`\n- Applies `normalizeReferralEarning` to all items in the array\n- Returns object with paginated metadata\n\n### 8. Pending Balance Query with Multiple Branches (Lines 809–829)\n```typescript\nasync getPendingBalance(wallet) {\n  const rows = await sql<{ pending: string }[]>`\n    SELECT COALESCE(\n      (\n        SELECT SUM(referrer_earned_lamports)\n        FROM referral_earnings WHERE referrer_wallet = ${wallet}\n      ), 0\n    ) + COALESCE(\n      (\n        SELECT SUM(referee_rebate_lamports)\n        FROM referral_earnings WHERE referee_wallet = ${wallet}\n      ), 0\n    ) - COALESCE(\n      (\n        SELECT SUM(amount_lamports)\n        FROM referral_claims WHERE wallet = ${wallet} AND status IN ('pending', 'processing', 'completed')\n      ), 0\n    ) AS pending\n  `;\n  return rows[0]!.pending;\n}\n```\nCalculates pending balance by subtracting claims from total earnings. References `referral_claims` table (which you'll need to add methods for if claims support is new).\n\n## General Query Patterns Summary\n\n1. **Type generics**: Always include type: `sql<RowType[]>\\`...\\``\n2. **Parameter binding**: Use `${variable}` directly (postgres.js handles escaping)\n3. **RETURNING ***: Always get back the full row after INSERT/UPDATE\n4. **Normalization**: Convert all numeric fields from DB strings to `Number` before returning\n5. **Optional returns**: Use `rows[0]` for undefined handling\n6. **Non-null returns**: Use `rows[0]!` when you know the query must succeed\n7. **Arrays**: Return `rows.map(normalize)` for lists\n8. **Parallel queries**: Use `Promise.all()` for independent queries\n9. **Pagination**: Use `OFFSET (page-1)*limit LIMIT limit`, fetch count separately\n\n---\n\n## Key Referral Tables (Inferred from Methods)\n\nBased on the code, these tables exist:\n- `referral_codes` — wallet, code, created_at, updated_at\n- `referral_links` — referrer_wallet, referee_wallet, created_at\n- `referral_earnings` — referrer_wallet, referee_wallet, round_id, game_type, wager_lamports, fee_lamports, referrer_earned_lamports, referrer_rate_bps, referee_rebate_lamports, referee_rebate_rate_bps, created_at\n- `referral_claims` — wallet, amount_lamports, status (referenced but no methods yet)\n\nYou now have the complete architectural blueprint for adding new referral-related methods. Follow the established patterns and you'll maintain consistency with the rest of the module."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a03d0a01a6abfe393 (use SendMessage with to: 'a03d0a01a6abfe393' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 50405\ntool_uses: 3\nduration_ms: 46867</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3e0bba06-3e2a-40d1-8fc4-6fd6659fa3ce","uuid":"3b436cf8-e2cf-4f48-ba1a-b725f2bf3d7a","timestamp":"2026-03-25T11:45:44.878Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Find and read the backend db.ts file in sources/rng-utopia/services/backend/. I need to see:\n1. The existing referral-related types and methods (ReferralCode, ReferralLink, ReferralEarning interfaces, and all insert/get methods)\n2. The Db interface definition - specifically the referral method signatures\n3. The createDb() function and how methods are implemented\n4. Any existing pattern for transactions or status updates\n\nFocus on the referral sections but also show me the general patterns used (e.g., how other methods like insertReferralEarning are implemented). Be thorough - I need the full picture to add new methods.","agentId":"a03d0a01a6abfe393","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect. I've read the entire db.ts file. Here's the comprehensive summary you need:\n\n## Referral-Related Types (Lines 127–166)\n\n```typescript\nexport interface ReferralCode {\n  id: number;\n  wallet: string;\n  code: string;\n  created_at: Date;\n  updated_at: Date;\n}\n\nexport interface ReferralLink {\n  id: number;\n  referrer_wallet: string;\n  referee